tweet_text: @Toyota @ToyotaMotorCorp #ToyotaWarAgainstHandicappedPeople I am writing to express my deep dissatisfaction and concern with Toyota's recent actions, which have left me and my family feeling disappointed and discriminated against. This ordeal centers around a brand new Toyota Camry that my uncle purchased in 2013, and a subsequent motor failure that led to Toyota's offer of a $2,000 voucher for a new car. Regrettably, Toyota's refusal to honor this voucher when purchasing a new, accessible Sienna for my handicapped daughter has left us deeply disheartened. My uncle's Toyota Camry served us well for ten years, accumulating only 120,000 miles, which is considerably less than one would typically expect from a Toyota vehicle. We understand that automobiles wear down over time, but a motor failure of this magnitude after just a decade is quite unusual, especially considering Toyota's reputation for quality and longevity. When we approached Toyota, they offered us a $2,000 voucher as compensation, seemingly to ease the burden of having to purchase a new vehicle. As a family with a handicapped daughter, our needs extend beyond the ordinary. It became necessary to purchase a wheelchair-accessible van to accommodate her requirements. We turned to A&J Mobility, a reputable handicap vehicle dealer, known for converting Toyota Sienna vans to make them accessible for individuals like my daughter. We expected to apply the $2,000 voucher towards the purchase of a new, accessible Sienna as it would have been the most practical choice for us. However, our disappointment knows no bounds when Toyota refused to honor the voucher for the purchase of the accessible Sienna. This decision by Toyota has not only left us feeling discriminated against due to our family's unique needs. The refusal to extend the voucher to a more suitable vehicle for our handicapped daughter is not only unprofessional but also deeply inhumane. We understand that corporate policies and terms may exist, but in this situation, where we have been loyal customers of Toyota and are faced with an extraordinary need, we had expected more compassion and understanding from a company of Toyota's stature. This ordeal has left us questioning Toyota's commitment to its customers and, more importantly, its consideration for individuals with special needs. In light of this situation, I kindly request that Toyota reviews its decision to deny the voucher's application towards the accessible Sienna we purchased through A&J Mobility. It is my hope that Toyota will reconsider this decision and make the necessary amendments to better reflect the values of fairness and compassion that we expect from a renowned company such as Toyota. I look forward to your prompt response and resolution of this matter. Please understand that this experience has had a significant impact on our family, and we hope for a positive resolution that will restore our faith in Toyota as a responsible and customer-centric corporation.
